[normal]Supplementary [bold]written evidence submitted by [bold]the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills [bold](WSC0105)[bold]Q 172-173[bold]:  Could the Government confirm who is responsible for gathering data on gender diversity in STEM? [bold]There is no single body tasked with pulling together all dat
[normal]a
[normal] on gender diversity 
[normal]in STEM
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Diversity within STEM is an issue which is of interest across government with specific areas of responsibility resting with individual departments
[normal] and sponsored bodies
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It should be noted that, unlike for academic subjects, there is not an agr
[normal]eed classification of jobs as STEM or non-STEM.  Some judgement has to necessarily be used in analysing data to build up a picture of the 'STEM workforce', and different classifications can give slightly different results
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As part of the BIS-
[normal]funded STEM diversity programme, the Royal Society 
[normal]is
[normal] carrying out a study 
[normal]of the 
[normal]diversity of the STEM workforce
[normal].  This study draws on data from several sources to build a comprehensive picture. 
[normal] It will outline a new categorisation of the STEM workforce.
[normal]  
[normal]Their report 
[normal]will be published early in 2014 and will help us to understand further where women
[normal],
[normal] and other underrepresented groups, go when they leave STEM education or careers. 
[normal] The Royal Academy of Engineering has also carried out analysis of the engin
[normal]eering workforce 
[normal]as
[normal] part of the STEM diversity programme.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q 174-176[bold]: Does the Government have any data on where women go when they leave academic STEM research careers?[bold]There is no single source of data for people leaving academic research careers as this
[normal] information would be held by the HEIs individually and would require evidence from exit interviews being collated.
[normal]There is information available on people leaving academic study, and
[normal] 
[normal]the HESA Destinations of Leavers from Higher Education (DLHE) Survey is the most authoritative source of data of where people go on completing first degrees and post graduate degrees.  
