[normal]Q: [bold]We would like a consistent time series showing total government funding for initiatives to increase diversity and equality in the workforce in [bold]STEM in each year of the current and previous spending review period.  Could you please provide us with figures on total government funding in each year from 2008-09 to 2014-15 for initiatives specifically aimed at promoting diversity and equality in STEM [bold]careers funded Government, including those administered or funded by NDPBs such as the national academies and research councils.[bold]In line with the Government’s approach to mainstream equality and diversity
[normal],
[normal] many of our programmes contribute to the aim of in
[normal]creasing the diversity of the STEM workforce.  Table 1 below shows the funding for equality and diversity specific projects.  Table 2 shows funding for our wider programme to stimulate the STEM pipeline and which contributes to the equality and diversity i
[normal]ssue.  The tables include BIS funded programmes and those of some partner bodies including those specifically listed by the Committee.   It should be noted that the National Academies are not NDPBs.  
[normal]They are independent, self-governing bodies
[normal] that receive
[normal] Government funding for specific programmes and projects
[normal].  
[normal]The Higher Education Funding Council for England
[normal] 
[normal](HEFCE) allocates funding to promote widening participation in higher education, some of which supports outreach to students
[normal] from disadvantaged bac
[normal]kgrounds
[normal] who will go on to study STEM subjects.
[normal]The Research Councils support for promoting equality and diversity in STEM careers is embedded within the Vitae® Programme
[normal] and its focus on the implementation of the Concordat to Support the Career Developme
[normal]nt of Researchers.
[normal] 
[normal] Vitae is funded by RCUK and the UK Funding Bodies.
[normal]The Concordat to Support the Career Development of Researchers sets out a vision of working practices, roles and responsibilities that the signatories believe will further the attractiv
[normal]eness and sustainability of research careers in the UK, and thus ensure the continued provision of well-trained, talented and motivated researchers that is essential to the continuation of our research excellence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 'Every researcher counts'
[normal] 
[normal]resources 
[normal]to improve equality and diversity for research staff within the HE sector was funded by HEFCE with support from
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the other HE funding bodies and is being delivered by Vitae. This project has developed a network of equality and diversity champions; produced 
[normal]resources and case studies for staff developers to embed in training materials for PIs and supervisors and disseminate resources and case studies through national and regional events. The next stages of the project are now also embedded within the Vitae pr
[normal]ogramme
[normal].
